{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1113"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1113"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.04,0.09,0.5,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97809"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1113"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1209"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97809"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents with a one-month history of intermittent pain on swallowing. These symptoms occur about twice a week and usually when he has eaten something spicy. He has a 12-year history of gastro-oesophageal reflux and takes an antacid when his symptoms become troublesome. He is overweight (BMI 29), but has lost 5 kg over the last two months after he started going to the gym. He is otherwise in good health and physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proton-pump inhibitor trial","Oesophageal manometry","Barium swallow","Endoscopy","CT chest and abdomen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient describes several \u201cred flag\u201d or \u201calarm\u201d symptoms occurring in the setting of gastro-oesophageal reflux. He has intermittent pain on swallowing (odynophagia) and weight loss - of course the weight loss might be intentional.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlarm symptoms include:\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOdynophagia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDysphagia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnintentional weight loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematemesis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese symptoms require prompt recognition and investigation via \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E for upper GI malignancy. It is still most likely that the patient\u0027s odynophagia will be due to reflux oesophagitis rather than malignancy. A CT chest and abdomen would only be necessary for staging the extent of malignancy following diagnosis on biopsy taken during endoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA therapeutic trial of a proton-pump inhibitor (PPI) would be appropriate in a patient with gastro-oesophageal reflux disease \u003Cem\u003Ewithout \u003C/em\u003Ealarm features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBarium swallow and oesophageal manometry may be considered if endoscopy was normal and there was suspicion of an anatomical or functional cause for reflux.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early endoscopy is essential for all patients with GORD and alarm symptoms to rule out upper GI malignancy"],"references":["Gastro-oesophageal Reflux Disease in Adults. 5th ed. Mulgrave, Victoria; 2011. Available from: https://www.gesa.org.au/public/13/files/Education%20%26%20Resources/Clinical%20Practice%20Resources/GORD/Reflux_Disease.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T14:56:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T14:56:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1113"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97809"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Under